/td><td valign=top bgcolor=d1c3b5 class=headings><font color=#000000>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uedwarddunai.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Edward Dunai</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/6/02 9:40:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1158.topic&index=48>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Of course...</span><hr size=1> I'm 'blindly' American, that is the very essence of International Statesmanship.  Remember, Buran, nationstates do NOT have friends, they do not have morals, they do not have ethics... they have interests.  The US will act in its own self-interest, just as will any other nation state.<br>
<br>
When the US self-interest is to care about the deaths of foreign nationals, the US will do so, when it is not in the US self-interest to care about them, then the US will not care.  Either way the United States will come under criticism, either for 'interfering in the sovereign affairs' of a smaller nation and being the big bully on the block, or for 'not caring' about the problems facing smaller nations.  Bluntly, the United States is currently the top dog in international affairs, and the rest of the dogs will spend most of their time yapping at the top dog.  This is not a statement of boastful pride or vanity, but merely fact.  As of now, the United States is the global hegemon, the only Nation State capable of projecting power on a global basis.<br>
<br>
Historically speaking, the US has been rather passive in the last 50 years or so responding to threats and deaths to its citizens overseas, especially in comparison to both other nations and history.  Theodore Roosevelt dispatched the entire Atlantic Fleet to Morocco to pressure the Sultan into securing the release of a man who *might* have been an American citizen and who had been kidnapped by rebels.  12 Battleships, 6 Armored Cruisers, about two dozen destroyers, and auxilaries... dispatched across the Atlantic over a single *possible* citizen in trouble.  During the Iranian Revolution the Soviet Union had 4 diplomats held hostage, the Soviet Military threatened to engage in a border incursion into Iran in which every day those four diplomats were held they would kill 400 Iranians.  Iran returned the hostages 2 days after the threat, and before the killing actually started, and never again threatened Russian nationals.<br>
<br>
Nation states are different than interpersonal relations, and the same rules do not apply.  Nation states are, by nature, amoral entities, at the level of international relations, common morality no longer applies.  The whole question of 'right and wrong' is not often asked, but rather the question is of capabilities and interests, the callous, brutal arithmetic of power.<br>
<br>
If the United States had reacted to the USS Cole, the Khofar Towers, the embassy bombings, the first WTC attack, the Beirut Marine Barracks bombing, as energetically and forcefully as the United States, Great Britain, Germany, Russia and Japan reacted to the Boxer rebellion in China, the terrorist threat would have never reached 9/11.  It was in attempting to inject morals, and 'multilateralism' into international affairs that paralyzed responding to previous attacks by the Radical Islamic Fundamentalists, thus emboldening them to greater acts of terror.  The US, through its actions, appeared 'soft', and became more and more of a target, after all, we hadn't reacted to previous attacks, but rather lobbed a few cruise missiles at empty huts.<br>
<br>
Israel is currently in the process of a much more rapid progression through the same process.  At the beginning of the Al Aqsa Intifada they responded rather anemically (and were damned regardless), attacking known terrorist installations after warning everybody to leave, trying to treat the terrorist threat as a law enforcement problem, and not a military one.  The attacks continued, and escalated, and now Israel is at the point that the US reached on 9/11.  Now Israel is pretty much adopting the Bush Doctrine vis a vis terror, and striking directly at the terrorists where they live, where they hide, and rooting them out.  Nobody asks why the UN operated refugee camps were functioning as arsenals for terrorists, why UN buildings were used as armories... why the UN stood by and watched as Hezbollah terrorists kidnapped and murdered 5 Israelis from the Israeli side of the border with Lebanon.<br>
<br>
Irexes, at the scale of personal relations, yes, 1 US life = 1 Afghan life etc etc etc.  But that is personal morality.  In the realm of international affairs, 1 'my country' life is greater than any number of 'other country' lives.  Why?  Bluntly, those 'other country' lives don't pay taxes and don't vote.  It's not 'jingoism', its reality, it is how nation states manage their affairs.  The UK is equally callous in its International Relations, elsewise explain Rwanda?  1 UK life was more valuable than however many hundreds of thousands of Rwandans who died to the genocide their, why else didn't the UK send in forces to secure peace?  The Royal Marines and Army are certainly capable of dealing with tribal fighters... Every nation, from Albania to Zimbawye, operates under the same calculus of interests.<br>
