</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/unakath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nakath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 161<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/7/02 1:52:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1158.topic&index=55>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Duty, Patriotism, and Morals</span><hr size=1> I utterly disagree with the idea that nations are exempt from a moral basis for behavior. Ethics and morals are part of what separates us from animals and are, in many ways, what makes society possible. For our government to feel that it is exempt is horrifying, for you to think they are exempt is nauseating.<br>
<br>
Heagan, I was a tax collector for five years, does that make me your lesser because I wasn't in the military? Do I get fewer rights? Is my voice diminished? Unless you were in a war, I GUARANTEE I was shot at more than you were.<br>
<br>
Rights are Duties. Period. My freedom of speech, is a right and therefore, it is a duty. I exercise it frequently and thougtfully. You are wrong suggest otherwise.<br>
<br>
I think that if you opened your mind and your eyes, you would see that very soon, we will have to choose whether we wish our government to continue its immoral and inethical course or whether we want to set a new example and make a paradigm shift to a better way of doing things. Our current course is headed for destruction. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uedwarddunai.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Edward Dunai</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/7/02 2:40:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1158.topic&index=56>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Nakath...</span><hr size=1> You aren't listening to what I'm saying.<br>
<br>
International Affairs are by their very nature and practice amoral.  Morality, ethics, friendships, et al do not apply in the decisions of nation-states, only their interests.<br>
<br>
Those interests can, indeed, be 'moral' and 'ethical' if morality and ethics coincide with interests, but no nation state can afford to allow mere morality and ethics to overtake its interests, because if it does, it is quite possible that the 'moral' and 'ethical' decisions will lead to the deaths of citizens for no actual gain.<br>
<br>
Nation-states do not deal with issues at the same level as you or I do, when a nation state acts, it is quite possible that large numbers of people will die directly by either action or inaction, and oftentimes people will die either way, therefore, no nation state can be justified in acting in anything other than its own interests, because to throw away the lives of its citizens on things outside of its interest is amongst the worst things a nation state can do.<br>
<br>
Now in the practices and execution of these interests is where ethics and morality occur, where the leaders make the ethical decisions between options for attaining the nations interests.<br>
<br>
